                <p>Dr. Ken Hargreaves received his D.D.S. from Georgetown University School of Dentistry and his Ph.D.
                    in physiology from the Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences in Bethesda, MD. He also
                    completed a postdoctoral fellowship in clinical and basic pain research at the National Institute of
                    Health and his residency in endodontics from the University of Minnesota.</p>

                <p>He joined the University of Texas Health Science Center at San Antonio, as Professor and Chair of the
                    Department of Endodontics in 1997, and is jointly appointed as a professor in the Departments of
                    Pharmacology and Physiology and Surgery (Medical School).</p>

                <p>His area of research focuses on the <a>pharmacology of pain and inflammation</a> and currently he
                    serves as a private investigator or co-private investigator on $30 million in NIH research grants.
                    He has received an NIH MERIT Award and the 2013 UT Health San Antonio Presidential Distinguished
                    Senior Research Scholar Award.</p>

                <p>He has published 160 papers, two textbooks, and has five patents issued/pending. Among these papers
                    are the description and validation of the “Hargreaves method,” which is broadly recognized as a
                    standard method for evaluating new analgesic drugs, and is in the top 5 percent of all papers cited
                    in the field of pain research.</p>

                <h2 class="sans-serif h5 bold"> Education</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>B.A., Neurobiology, University of California Berkeley, 1977</li>
